{"rawJson":null,"m_plot":null,"m_cast":"Steve Martin as Larry Hubbard | Charles Grodin as Warren Evans | Judith Ivey as Iris | Steve Lawrence as Jack Fenwick | Robyn Douglass as Danielle | Merv Griffin as Himself | Joyce Brothers as Herself | Julie K. Payne as rental agent | Roger Robinson as greeting card supervisor | Nicholas Mele as maître d’ | Loni Anderson as Herself (uncredited)","m_reception":"The Lonely Guy received mixed reviews from critics.[citation needed] It holds a 48% rating on Rotten Tomatoes.","m_production":"The scene in which Steve Martin runs across the 59th Street Bridge to Queens was in fact all filmed on location in 1984 and Martin (who was a runner in real-life) actually made the run. He began his run on the Manhattan side of the bridge and then ran (mid lane) to Queensboro Plaza, then branching towards Astoria. Martin ran under the elevated N/W-Train Subway line, up 31st Street, meeting with a police officer on the corner of 31st and Newtown Avenue and all the way to 28th Avenue and 31st. Although edited out of actual sequence Martin eventually enters the old church (which still stands) at 51 31st Street, Astoria - only to realize he has interrupted the wrong wedding.","m_sequel":null,"m_based_on":null,"m_directed_by":"Arthur Hiller","m_produced_by":"Arthur Hiller","m_screenplay_by":null,"m_story_by":null,"m_starring":"Steve Martin | Charles Grodin | Judith Ivey | Steve Lawrence | Robyn Douglass","m_music_by":"Jerry Goldsmith","m_cinematography":"Victor J. Kemper","m_edited_by":"Raja Gosnell William H. Reynolds","m_production_company":"Aspen Film Society","m_distributed_by":"Universal Pictures","m_release_dates":"January 27, 1984 (1984-01-27) |  |  |  | ","m_running_time":"90 minutes","m_country":"United States","m_language":"English","m_budget":null,"m_box_office":"$5,718,573 | The Lonely Guy is a 1984 romantic comedy film, directed by Arthur Hiller and starring Steve Martin. The screenplay is credited to Ed. Weinberger and Stan Daniels (of